          "body": "Verse 5 is the chapter's most compressed and most expansive statement. It begins with 'afterward' — the single word that severs the era of desolation from the era of return. Three verbs drive the restoration: *return*, *seek*, and *come trembling*. The first two are active and directed: the sons of Israel will return and seek the LORD their God and David their king. The seeking is not passive waiting but active pursuit — *baqash*, to search diligently. The third is affective: they will come trembling (*pachad*) to the LORD and to His goodness. The trembling is not terror but awe-reverence — the response of a people who understand what they had abandoned and what it cost to retrieve them. Critically, verse 5 names two objects of seeking: Yahweh their God AND David their king. This pairing cannot be satisfied by any post-exilic restoration under Zerubbabel or Ezra. No Davidic king ruled after the exile who could be identified as the fulfillment. Reformed and premillennial interpreters alike — Calvin, John Owen, and contemporary scholars like Thomas McComiskey (*The Minor Prophets*, Baker) — read 'David their king' as a messianic title referring to the descendant of David, the one who reunites the divided kingdom under one shepherd (Ezekiel 37:24-25). The phrase 'in the last days' (*acharit hayamim*) seals the eschatological identification."
