          "body": "Hosea 3, read as a whole, is not primarily a marriage story or a sociological case study — it is a compressed gospel. A faithful covenant partner seeks a faithless one who has gone into bondage to her own idols (3:1). He finds her, pays the redemption price from his own resources (3:2), places her under a structured discipline that suspends the old patterns without yet restoring the full relationship (3:3). During this 'many days' she is kept and held, neither abandoned nor yet fully restored. At the appointed time — 'afterward,' 'in the last days' — the one who was sought returns, seeks, and comes trembling to the goodness of the one who bought her (3:5). Jonathan Edwards and John Owen both argued that the covenant of redemption — the eternal arrangement within the Godhead by which the Son undertakes the rescue of the unfaithful bride — is precisely what passages like Hosea 3 are enacting in prophetic biography. The text is not an analogy for human marriage ethics; it is a revelation of divine covenant love through the medium of a human marriage. The New Testament completes the picture: the price Hosea paid was silver and barley; the price Yahweh pays for His Israel is the life of His own Son (Revelation 5:9)."
