        "excerpt": "Go again, love a woman who is loved by her husband, yet an adulteress, even as the LORD loves the sons of Israel, though they turn to other gods.",
        "body": "The first word of the chapter in Hebrew is Yahweh's direct speech to Hosea, and its content is a command to resume love toward a woman who has given no indication of repentance. The grammar is imperative — *lekh od*, 'go again.' The 'again' (*od*) is the chapter's first hermeneutical key. Hosea is not beginning a new love; he is re-enacting the original covenant love despite all that has intervened. The command does not wait for the woman to signal readiness. It precedes her return by the entire span of the chapter.\n\nThe theological ground of the command is explicit in verse 1's second half: 'even as the LORD loves the sons of Israel, though they turn to other gods and love raisin cakes.' The *even as* makes the analogy not illustrative but constitutive — Hosea is not being asked to imitate divine love from a distance; he is being enrolled as the visible sign of it. What God is currently doing toward Israel (loving an adulteress people who prefer the Baals) is what Hosea is now commanded to do in his domestic situation. The sign-act embeds theology in biography.\n\nThe raisin cakes (*ashishah*) deserve attention. In Jeremiah 7:18 and 44:19, the same offering appears in the context of worship offered to the 'queen of heaven' — Asherah or Ishtar. These are not casual food but ritual offerings at Canaanite fertility shrines. Israel's love for them is not mere spiritual forgetfulness; it is an organized, liturgically sustained alternative devotion. The worship of the Baals had its own sacrificial calendar, its own rites, its own shrines. Israel has not simply drifted; it has constructed a competing worship system. The love for raisin cakes is the love for an entire alternative liturgical order.\n\nThe scandal of the command is therefore theological before it is personal. The question the text poses is not 'how could Hosea love her?' but 'how can Yahweh love Israel?' The answer is not given in Hosea 3 but only gestured toward: it lies in the nature of God's covenant, in the promise He made to the fathers (Deuteronomy 7:7-9), and — the New Testament will complete — in the Lamb who was slain before the foundation of the world (Revelation 13:8).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Od* (again) — also translated 'still,' as in 'still love her.' The ambiguity is productive: Hosea is to go again (resumption of action) while Yahweh still loves Israel (continuity of love). *Ahav* (love) occurs three times in verse 1 — the repetition insists that love is the chapter's load-bearing theme. *Ashishah* (raisin cakes) — pressed grape-cakes, cult offerings at Canaanite fertility shrines."
