        "excerpt": "So I bought her for myself for fifteen shekels of silver and a homer and a half of barley.",
        "body": "Verse 2 records the act of obedience in the most prosaic terms possible: a price, two commodities, a transaction. The verb *karah* (to purchase, to acquire) is not the standard marriage word; it belongs to the world of commerce, more commonly associated with acquiring goods or hired labor. The choice of vocabulary is deliberate — the woman is in a state from which she must be purchased, not merely invited.\n\nThe price — fifteen shekels of silver and a homer and a half of barley — has generated significant discussion. The standard slave redemption price in Exodus 21:32 was thirty shekels of silver. A homer and a half of barley at the going rate for the period equates to approximately fifteen shekels of silver, bringing the total to roughly thirty shekels. Hosea pays the full slave-price: half in silver, half in kind. The woman's condition is that of one in debt-slavery or actual servitude — she cannot return on her own initiative. The return requires an outside redeemer who pays the price and takes her for himself.\n\nThe theological resonance with the wider Old Testament is dense. The *go'el* (kinsman-redeemer) tradition in Ruth and Leviticus 25 establishes redemption as an act of the nearest-of-kin who pays the price to restore what was lost. Hosea acts as go'el to a woman who has forfeited her place in his household. And the analogy in verse 1 makes Yahweh the go'el of Israel — the nearest-of-kin who will not abandon His people to the slave-market of their own idolatry but will pay the redemption price to reclaim them.\n\nFor the New Testament interpreter, the typology is sharp without being strained. 1 Corinthians 6:20 ('you were bought with a price') and 1 Peter 1:18-19 ('you were not redeemed with perishable things like silver or gold... but with the precious blood of Christ') both inhabit the same redemption-purchase logic. The difference is one of currency: Hosea pays silver and barley; the redemption of Israel — and of every Gomer-people — costs the life of the Son.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Karah* (to buy) — not the standard term for marriage or betrothal; it belongs to the sphere of commercial acquisition. Its use here implies the woman is in a bondage that requires a purchase price to break. *Chomer* (homer) — a dry measure of approximately 220 liters; the homer and a half (*letekh*) of barley was the cheapest staple grain, underlining that Hosea was paying in part from whatever he could gather."
