        "body": "Hosea's instruction to the woman in verse 3 is counterintuitive in two ways. First, the restraint is mutual: 'so I will also be toward you' — Hosea withholds himself from the full resumption of the conjugal relationship during the same 'many days' he requires of her. This is not punitive cruelty but structured discipline. The old patterns — her harlotry, and presumably his own pain-driven withdrawal — must both be suspended before the covenant can be fully resumed. The 'many days' is a holding period that protects the future relationship by refusing to rush into it.\n\nVerse 4 applies this directly to Israel with a precision that makes the sign-act's purpose unmistakable. The causal connector 'for' (*ki*) establishes that the woman's 'many days' is the interpretive key to Israel's 'many days.' The six things Israel will be without constitute a total stripping: king and prince (political order), sacrifice and sacred pillar (worship apparatus, one legitimate and one syncretic), ephod and household idols (priestly and divinatory instruments, one Yahwistic and one Canaanite). The list is deliberately comprehensive. God does not merely remove the idols; He removes the entire structure through which Israel has organized its common life — political, cultic, and domestic.\n\nThis comprehensive stripping has divided interpreters at the point of the ephod and sacrifice. Thomas McComiskey (*The Minor Prophets*, Baker Exegetical) argues that the removal of legitimate apparatus alongside the illegitimate is intentional: during the exile, Israel will be unable to maintain even proper sacrifice because the Temple will be destroyed and the Levitical order disrupted. The discipline is not partial (remove only the Baals) but total (remove everything Israel was using to meet God — or to substitute for meeting God). The result is a period of spiritual nakedness designed to produce hunger for the real.\n\nFrom a premillennial perspective, the 'many days' cannot be satisfied by the Babylonian exile of seventy years. The northern kingdom (the primary audience of Hosea) was exiled by Assyria in 722 BC and never returned as a distinct national entity. The restoration of verse 5 — with its Davidic king and eschatological 'last days' — requires a fulfillment that extends beyond anything in the historical postexilic period. Calvin himself, though amillennial, acknowledged that 'David their king' in verse 5 requires a messianic referent: no post-exilic ruler of Davidic lineage exercised the kind of kingship the text anticipates.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rav yom* (many days) — the same phrase in vv. 3 and 4 creates the structural parallel between the woman's discipline and Israel's desolation. *Matstsevah* (sacred pillar) — standing stones erected at Canaanite high places; prohibited in Deuteronomy 16:22. *Teraphim* (household idols) — the same objects Rachel stole from Laban in Genesis 31:19; associated with divination and ancestor veneration."
