        "number": 4,
        "title": "The eschatological return — seeking, trembling, and coming to His goodness in the last days",
        "range": "3:5",
        "excerpt": "Afterward the sons of Israel will return and seek the LORD their God and David their king; and they will come trembling to the LORD and to His goodness in the last days.",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the chapter's eschatological resolution, and its two-word opening — 'afterward' (*achar*) — is the most load-bearing adverb in the chapter. The word severs what precedes from what follows. The 'many days' of stripping is real, sustained, and complete; but it is not the last word. After that period, a categorically different movement begins.\n\nThe restoration is described in four verbs accumulating in rapid succession: *return*, *seek*, *come*, *tremble*. The first two (return and seek) are the active posture of Israel moving toward Yahweh and the Davidic king. The latter two describe the manner of arrival: they come trembling (*pachad*) — a reverential awe that is not mere fear but the appropriate response of a people who understand what they had abandoned and what it cost to retrieve them. Crucially, their arrival is *to the LORD and to His goodness* — the Hebrew *tuv* (goodness) is not abstract moral excellence but concrete covenantal beneficence: health, prosperity, delight, shalom. The people come trembling not to a court of judgment but to a table of goodness. Psalm 31:19 uses the same word: 'How great is Your goodness (*tuv*), which You have stored up for those who fear You.'\n\nThe identification 'David their king' is the verse's most theologically pregnant phrase. By Hosea's time, the Davidic kingdom had already been divided for two centuries. The northern kingdom had no Davidic king and showed no political interest in acquiring one. To say that Israel (the north) will seek 'David their king' is to project a reunification under the Davidic covenant that transcends any merely political restoration. McComiskey, Brevard Childs, and the patristic tradition all read this as a messianic title. The New Testament identification is supplied by Luke 1:32-33 (the Son of David who will reign on David's throne forever) and Ezekiel 37:24-25 (one shepherd, David, ruling the reunited Israel in the last days). Reformed scholars (Owen, Calvin, Edwards) and dispensational premillennialists alike converge here: 'David their king' in Hosea 3:5 is a title for the Messiah, not a prediction of a literal resurrected David.\n\nThe phrase 'in the last days' (*acharit hayamim*) seals the eschatological reading. The phrase occurs in Isaiah 2:2, Micah 4:1, Daniel 10:14, and Numbers 24:14 — always to denote the final period of history toward which all prophetic vision moves. Hosea places the restoration of Israel within that horizon. This is not primarily about the return from Babylon; it is about the end-of-history seeking that the New Testament associates with Israel's future, Paul's hope in Romans 11:25-27, and the completion of redemptive history under the returning Davidic King.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Acharit hayamim* (in the last days / the latter end of the days) — a fixed eschatological formula in OT prophecy, appearing also in Isaiah 2:2; Micah 4:1; Daniel 10:14. *Pachad* (trembling) — not *yir'ah* (fear) but the trembling of awe; used in Psalm 2:11 ('serve the LORD with fear and rejoice with trembling'). *Tuv* (goodness) — concrete covenantal beneficence, not abstract moral quality."
